          "body": "The chapter's final movement (1:7-11) is a formal inventory of Temple vessels, catalogued by name, type, and number, formally transferred from Cyrus's treasurer to Sheshbazzar, the prince of Judah. The vessels had been looted by Nebuchadnezzar and placed in the house of his gods (1:7) — a deliberate act of religious triumphalism, asserting Babylon's gods over Yahweh. Their return reverses that claim. The counting is not bureaucratic padding; it is theological statement. Sixty-nine specific items are named (1:9-10), totaling 5,400 gold and silver pieces (1:11). The precision insists that not one vessel was lost, destroyed, or retained. What Nebuchadnezzar took, Yahweh recovered. The Second Temple is not starting over — it is receiving back what was wrongly taken. Sacred continuity is maintained from Solomon's Temple through exile into restoration."
