          "title": "The open door and the willing heart",
          "body": "Cyrus's decree was universal: 'whoever there is among you of all His people, let him go up' (1:3). The door was open to every exile. Yet verse 5 records that only 'everyone whose spirit God had stirred' arose to go. Most stayed. Jewish tradition and the later chapters of Ezra-Nehemiah confirm that the majority of the exile community remained in Babylon — many had built houses, started businesses, and put down roots across the 70 years (cf. Jeremiah 29:5-7). This is not condemned in the text, but it is noted. The open door required a willing heart. The willing heart was a God-given gift. Those who went did not go because they were morally superior — they went because God had stirred them. And yet they arose. The chapter's implicit challenge is perennial: when God opens a door to rebuild what has been lost or broken, do you arise? The resources are promised (1:4), the mission is clear (1:3), the sovereign hand is evident (1:1). The question is whether your spirit has been stirred — and whether you will rise."
