        "excerpt": "Then the heads of fathers' households of Judah and Benjamin and the priests and the Levites arose, even everyone whose spirit God had stirred to go up and rebuild the house of the LORD which is in Jerusalem.",
        "body": "Verse 5 is the chapter's narrative pivot. Decree has been issued (1:1-4); now the people respond. The structure of the response is carefully described. First, the social and cultic leaders arise: heads of fathers' households (laity), priests, and Levites. This is not a mob exodus but an ordered, institution-shaped return — the same community structures that existed in pre-exilic Israel are intact and functional. The exile did not dissolve Israel's social organization.\n\nThe theological qualifier is precise: 'everyone whose spirit God had stirred.' The same *ur* used of Cyrus in verse 1 is used of the returnees in verse 5. The parallel is intentional and theologically loaded. God did not stir every exile's spirit — most remained in Babylon. He stirred a particular group, and that group arose. This is not a description of irresistible compulsion; the people make real choices to go. But those choices are grounded in a prior divine act on their inner life. The doctrine of God's sovereignty over human will is present here in narrative form — not as abstract theology but as the explanation for why some people obey and others do not when the same opportunity is extended to all.\n\nVerse 6 introduces the surrounding community's contribution. 'All those about them' — presumably both Jewish neighbors who chose not to return and gentile neighbors in the Babylonian diaspora — 'encouraged them' or 'strengthened their hands' (*chazaq*, reinforced, supported). The list is identical to what Cyrus commanded in verse 4: silver, gold, goods, cattle. The decree is being fulfilled precisely. But verse 6 adds a significant qualifier: this practical support came 'aside from all that was given as a freewill offering.' The total provision exceeded the official mandate. Voluntary generosity supplemented imperial command.\n\nThis pattern — governmental provision plus community generosity — is the Second Exodus signature. As Israel left Egypt with 'articles of silver and gold and clothing' given by the Egyptians (Exodus 12:35-36), the returnees leave Babylon with silver, gold, goods, and valuables given by their neighbors. Ezra's readers would have recognized the type immediately. Peter Davids notes (in his wider work on OT theology of return) that Ezra 1 positions the restoration as a new Exodus — not metaphorically but with the full weight of typological fulfillment.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chazaq* (strengthened/encouraged, 1:6) — literally 'to be strong, to strengthen the hands of.' It is the same word used when the elders of Israel 'strengthened the hands' of one another in communal endeavors. The word carries more than emotional encouragement; it implies tangible, material support."
